00:28:20.670 --> 00:28:27.150
on Mia [Spanish] poem parading
down Blackstone Avenue.

00:28:27.150 --> 00:28:32.200
And that voice, that poem has
reached all of us with the voices

00:28:32.200 --> 00:28:35.400
of our chamber singers and
now you have her voice,

00:28:35.400 --> 00:28:38.700
her encouragement and her energy.

00:28:38.700 --> 00:28:43.270
And then it makes me ask the
question what can a poem do?

00:28:43.270 --> 00:28:45.670
What can we do when
something takes place?

00:28:45.670 --> 00:28:48.750
Something that leaves us helpless?

00:28:48.750 --> 00:28:52.140
Something that's far
away, maybe it's Boston,

00:28:52.140 --> 00:28:57.900
maybe it's a terrible incident
and maybe it's the massacre

00:28:57.900 --> 00:29:00.950
that we all know about
in South Carolina.

00:29:00.950 --> 00:29:02.980
So I said what can I do?

00:29:02.980 --> 00:29:07.760
I think what we can all do is make
an offering, maybe just to meditate

00:29:07.760 --> 00:29:10.450
on it, maybe it's to say hello.

00:29:10.450 --> 00:29:13.170
Maybe it's to let go of some
of the things that keep us

00:29:13.170 --> 00:29:18.480
from being really intimate and
caring and maybe it's also a poem

00:29:18.480 --> 00:29:23.230
that we can write and
send to the people.

00:29:23.230 --> 00:29:28.740
And this poem, by poem speaks about
this and it was actually received

00:29:28.740 --> 00:29:33.960
in South Carolina and was put on
a newsletter throughout that area

00:29:33.960 --> 00:29:37.790
in particular and the church
where all this took place.

00:29:37.790 --> 00:29:42.640
Poem by poem, we can
end the violence.

